# Tutorials

## Using Postman to Make IM API Calls

### Introduction

The following details the process of using Postman application for authenticating the /login API in order to receive a signed JWT access token which can be used to call other Integration Manager RESTful API services. The user should provide the access token in each API call. The user can use any REST API client.

### Pre-requisites

- Download and install the Integration Manager application. Make sure the Integration Manager service is running and you have applied a license to it. For more details, please go through Integration Manager documentation available at docs.actian.com
- Make sure you have full access to the Actian Integration Manager API
- Download Postman from [https://www.getpostman.com/downloads/](https://www.getpostman.com/downloads/) and install it.

### Steps to get the Access token

1. Launch the Postman application.
2. In the header toolbar, click on &#39;New&#39; button. A window with the &#39;Create New&#39; tab appears.

![](data:image/*;base64,)

3. Click on &#39;Collection&#39;.
4. In the &#39;CREATE A NEW COLLECTION&#39; window, enter a name, for example, &#39;IM - login&#39;. Click on the &#39;Create&#39; button.
5. Hover the mouse over IM-login collection on the left side of the page.
6. Click on three dots symbol &#39;...&#39;, then click on &#39;Add Request&#39;.

![](data:image/*;base64,)

7. In the &#39;SAVE REQUEST&#39; window, enter a Request name, for example, &#39;Generate auth token&#39;. If you have given the collection name as &#39;IM - login&#39;, then you should see &#39;Save to IM - login&#39; button, click on it.

![](data:image/*;base64,)

8. In the left side of the page, under the collections, click on the collection &#39;IM - login&#39; and click on the new request to open it. On the right side, the request tab will be displayed.
9. Click on the GET HTTP method and change it to POST HTTP method.

![](data:image/*;base64,)

10. Enter [http://localhost:8080/api/login](http://localhost:8080/api/login) in the &#39;Enter request URL&#39; bar. Note: this is the default endpoint, but if you have a custom host and port defined, use that.
11. Click on the &#39;Headers&#39; tab and enter Key as &#39;Content-Type&#39; and enter the value &#39;application/json&#39;.

![](data:image/*;base64,)

12. Click on the &#39;Body tab&#39;, then choose the radio-button raw and enter the following and replace the &#39;string&#39; with a valid username and password respectively.
    {
    &quot;username&quot;: &quot;string&quot;,
    &quot;password&quot;: &quot;string&quot;
    }
13. Click on the &#39;Send&#39; button. Make sure your account has access to the API. You should see the response status as &#39;200 OK&#39; and receive the bearer token value in the response Body. Otherwise, if you get 401 Unauthorized error, see if you entered correct username and password in the request body. If you notice &quot;There was an error connecting to [http://localhost:8080/api/login](http://localhost:8080/api/login)&quot;, then make sure the Integration Manager service is running and then try again.

![](data:image/*;base64,)

14. Copy the access token value which is a very long gibberish value between the double quotes and we will use that in the following section.

### How to use the token to access other Integration Manager API services

You can set the access token to an environment variable to use it for a particular environment or set it up as global to use it across all environments. Let&#39;s use the access token without setting up a variable.

#### Without using variables

1. Create a new collection called &#39;Job Configuration&#39; and create a new GET request to get the list of Job Templates using the API: [http://localhost:8080/api/jobtemplates](http://localhost:8080/api/jobtemplates)
2. Click on the &#39;Authorization&#39; tab and choose &#39;TYPE&#39; as &#39;Bearer Token&#39;. Then on the right-hand side, paste the bearer token value in the Token field.
3. Click on Send.

![](data:image/*;base64,)

4. You should see the response status as &#39;200 OK&#39; and see the list of Job Templates in the response body.
5. When working with many API services, it becomes tedious to copy the Token to each API call, so an environment/global variable saves the time.

#### Using a global variable

1. Click on the eye icon which is in the top right-hand corner. Create a global variable by clicking on Edit under the Globals section.

![](data:image/*;base64,)

2. The &#39;MANAGE ENVIRONMENTS&#39; window appears. Click on &#39;Add a new variable&#39; field and type &#39;IM-TOKEN&#39;.
3. Under &#39;CURRENT VALUE&#39;, type &#39;Bearer {paste the value of the bearer token here}&#39;. Then click on SAVE button.

![](data:image/*;base64,)

4. Create a new GET request to get the list of Job Configurations using the API: [http://localhost:8080/api/jobconfigs](http://localhost:8080/api/jobconfigs)
5. Click on the &#39;Headers&#39; and enter &#39;Authorization&#39; in the Key field and enter { in the value, it displays the list of variables and choose &#39;IM-TOKEN&#39; variable Click on the Send button.

![](data:image/*;base64,)

6. You should see the response status as &#39;200 OK&#39; and see the list of Job Configurations in the response body.

![](data:image/*;base64,)

7. Similarly, you can set up an environment and define variables in it. Click [here](https://learning.getpostman.com/docs/postman/environments_and_globals/manage_environments/) for more information on managing environments.
8. Go through Integration Manager API documentation to find the available services.
